events.description: A Seljuk Turkish army successfully fights off the People's Crusade at the Battle of Civetot.
events.html: • 1096 – A Seljuk Turkish army successfully fights off the People's Crusade at the Battle of Civetot.

events.description: First Crusade: Crusaders led by Godfrey of Bouillon, Bohemund of Taranto, and Raymond IV, Count of Toulouse, begin the Siege of Antioch.
events.html: • 1097 – First Crusade: Crusaders led by Godfrey of Bouillon, Bohemund of Taranto, and Raymond IV, Count of Toulouse, begin the Siege of Antioch.

events.description: Japanese Emperor Go-Kameyama abdicates in favor of rival claimant Go-Komatsu.
events.html: • 1392 – Japanese Emperor Go-Kameyama abdicates in favor of rival claimant Go-Komatsu.

events.description: Martin Luther joins the theological faculty of the University of Wittenberg.
events.html: • 1512 – Martin Luther joins the theological faculty of the University of Wittenberg.

events.description: João Álvares Fagundes discovers the islands of Saint Pierre and Miquelon, bestowing them their original name of "Islands of the 11,000 Virgins".
events.html: • 1520 – João Álvares Fagundes discovers the islands of Saint Pierre and Miquelon, bestowing them their original name of "Islands of the 11,000 Virgins".

events.description: Tokugawa Ieyasu defeats the leaders of rival Japanese clans in the Battle of Sekigahara and becomes shōgun of Japan.
events.html: • 1600 – Tokugawa Ieyasu defeats the leaders of rival Japanese clans in the Battle of Sekigahara and becomes shōgun of Japan.

events.description: The flag of Taunton, Massachusetts is the first to include the word "Liberty".
events.html: • 1774 – The flag of Taunton, Massachusetts is the first to include the word "Liberty".

events.description: In Boston Harbor, the 44-gun United States Navy frigate USS Constitution is launched.
events.html: • 1797 – In Boston Harbor, the 44-gun United States Navy frigate USS Constitution is launched.

events.description: Napoleonic Wars: A British fleet led by Lord Nelson defeats a combined French and Spanish fleet under Admiral Villeneuve in the Battle of Trafalgar.
events.html: • 1805 – Napoleonic Wars: A British fleet led by Lord Nelson defeats a combined French and Spanish fleet under Admiral Villeneuve in the Battle of Trafalgar.

events.description: Portland cement is patented.
events.html: • 1824 – Portland cement is patented.

events.description: Florence Nightingale and a staff of 38 nurses are sent to the Crimean War.
events.html: • 1854 – Florence Nightingale and a staff of 38 nurses are sent to the Crimean War.

events.description: American Civil War: Union forces under Colonel Edward Baker are defeated by Confederate troops in the second major battle of the war.
events.html: • 1861 – American Civil War: Union forces under Colonel Edward Baker are defeated by Confederate troops in the second major battle of the war.

events.description: The Medicine Lodge Treaty is signed by southern Great Plains Indian leaders. The treaty requires Native American Plains tribes to relocate to a reservation in the western Indian Territory.
events.html: • 1867 – The Medicine Lodge Treaty is signed by southern Great Plains Indian leaders. The treaty requires Native American Plains tribes to relocate to a reservation in the western Indian Territory.

events.description: Thomas Edison applies for a patent for his design for an incandescent light bulb.
events.html: • 1879 – Thomas Edison applies for a patent for his design for an incandescent light bulb.

events.description: The Swiss Social Democratic Party is founded.
events.html: • 1888 – The Swiss Social Democratic Party is founded.

events.description: Opening ceremonies for the World's Columbian Exposition are held in Chicago, though because construction was behind schedule, the exposition did not open until May 1, 1893.
events.html: • 1892 – Opening ceremonies for the World's Columbian Exposition are held in Chicago, though because construction was behind schedule, the exposition did not open until May 1, 1893.

events.description: The capitulation of Tainan completes the Japanese conquest of Taiwan.
events.html: • 1895 – The capitulation of Tainan completes the Japanese conquest of Taiwan.

events.description: The 1907 Qaratog earthquake hits the borders of Uzbekistan and Tajikistan, killing between 12,000 and 15,000 people.
events.html: • 1907 – The 1907 Qaratog earthquake hits the borders of Uzbekistan and Tajikistan, killing between 12,000 and 15,000 people.

events.description: HMS Niobe arrives in Halifax Harbour to become the first ship of the Royal Canadian Navy.
events.html: • 1910 – HMS Niobe arrives in Halifax Harbour to become the first ship of the Royal Canadian Navy.

events.description: First Balkan War: The Greek navy completes the capture of the island of Lemnos for use as a forward base against the Dardanelles.
events.html: • 1912 – First Balkan War: The Greek navy completes the capture of the island of Lemnos for use as a forward base against the Dardanelles.[1]

events.description: President Warren G. Harding delivers the first speech by a sitting U.S. president against lynching in the Deep South.
events.html: • 1921 – President Warren G. Harding delivers the first speech by a sitting U.S. president against lynching in the Deep South.

events.description: A secret society in the Imperial Japanese Army launches an abortive coup d'état attempt.
events.html: • 1931 – A secret society in the Imperial Japanese Army launches an abortive coup d'état attempt.

events.description: The first edition of the Ernest Hemingway novel For Whom the Bell Tolls is published.
events.html: • 1940 – The first edition of the Ernest Hemingway novel For Whom the Bell Tolls is published.

events.description: World War II: The Kragujevac massacre against Serbian men and boys takes place.
events.html: • 1941 – World War II: The Kragujevac massacre against Serbian men and boys takes place.[2]

events.description: World War II: The Provisional Government of Free India is formally established in Japanese-occupied Singapore.
events.html: • 1943 – World War II: The Provisional Government of Free India is formally established in Japanese-occupied Singapore.

events.description: World War II: The first kamikaze attack damages HMAS Australia as the Battle of Leyte Gulf begins.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The first kamikaze attack damages HMAS Australia as the Battle of Leyte Gulf begins.

events.description: World War II: The Nemmersdorf massacre against German civilians takes place.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The Nemmersdorf massacre against German civilians takes place.

events.description: World War II: The city of Aachen falls to American forces after three weeks of fighting, the first German city to fall to the Allies.
events.html: • 1944 – World War II: The city of Aachen falls to American forces after three weeks of fighting, the first German city to fall to the Allies.

events.description: In the 1945 French legislative election French women vote for the first time.
events.html: • 1945 – In the 1945 French legislative election French women vote for the first time.

events.description: Korean War: Heavy fighting begins between British and Australian forces and North Koreans during the Battle of Yongju.
events.html: • 1950 – Korean War: Heavy fighting begins between British and Australian forces and North Koreans during the Battle of Yongju.

events.description: The Mau Mau Uprising in Kenya is defeated.
events.html: • 1956 – The Mau Mau Uprising in Kenya is defeated.

events.description: In New York City, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum opens to the public.
events.html: • 1959 – In New York City, the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum opens to the public.

events.description: President Dwight D. Eisenhower approves the transfer of all US Army space-related activities to NASA, including most of the Army Ballistic Missile Agency.
events.html: • 1959 – President Dwight D. Eisenhower approves the transfer of all US Army space-related activities to NASA, including most of the Army Ballistic Missile Agency.

events.description: Comet Ikeya–Seki approaches perihelion, passing 450,000 kilometers (279,617 miles) from the sun.
events.html: • 1965 – Comet Ikeya–Seki approaches perihelion, passing 450,000 kilometers (279,617 miles) from the sun.

events.description: A colliery spoil tip slips onto houses and a school in the village of Aberfan in Wales, killing 144 people, 116 of whom were schoolchildren.
events.html: • 1966 – A colliery spoil tip slips onto houses and a school in the village of Aberfan in Wales, killing 144 people, 116 of whom were schoolchildren.[3]

events.description: The National Mobilization Committee to End the War in Vietnam organizes a march of fifty thousand people from the Lincoln Memorial to the Pentagon.
events.html: • 1967 – The National Mobilization Committee to End the War in Vietnam organizes a march of fifty thousand people from the Lincoln Memorial to the Pentagon.

entities.name: National Mobilization Committee to End the War in Vietnam

events.description: The 1969 Somali coup d'état establishes a Marxist–Leninist administration.
events.html: • 1969 – The 1969 Somali coup d'état establishes a Marxist–Leninist administration.

events.description: A gas explosion kills 22 people at a shopping centre near Glasgow, Scotland.
events.html: • 1971 – A gas explosion kills 22 people at a shopping centre near Glasgow, Scotland.

events.description: Fred Dryer of the Los Angeles Rams becomes the first player in NFL history to score two safeties in the same game.
events.html: • 1973 – Fred Dryer of the Los Angeles Rams becomes the first player in NFL history to score two safeties in the same game.

events.description: Australian civilian pilot Frederick Valentich vanishes over the Bass Strait south of Melbourne, after reporting contact with an unidentified aircraft.
events.html: • 1978 – Australian civilian pilot Frederick Valentich vanishes over the Bass Strait south of Melbourne, after reporting contact with an unidentified aircraft.[4]

events.description: Moshe Dayan resigns from the Israeli government because of strong disagreements with Prime Minister Menachem Begin over policy towards the Arabs.
events.html: • 1979 – Moshe Dayan resigns from the Israeli government because of strong disagreements with Prime Minister Menachem Begin over policy towards the Arabs.

events.description: Andreas Papandreou becomes Prime Minister of Greece, ending an almost 50-year-long system of power dominated by conservative forces.
events.html: • 1981 – Andreas Papandreou becomes Prime Minister of Greece, ending an almost 50-year-long system of power dominated by conservative forces.

events.description: The metre is defined as the distance light travels in a vacuum in 1/299,792,458 of a second.
events.html: • 1983 – The metre is defined as the distance light travels in a vacuum in 1/299,792,458 of a second.

events.description: Niki Lauda claims his third and final Formula One Drivers' Championship Title by half a point ahead of McLaren team-mate Alain Prost at the Portuguese Grand Prix.
events.html: • 1984 – Niki Lauda claims his third and final Formula One Drivers' Championship Title by half a point ahead of McLaren team-mate Alain Prost at the Portuguese Grand Prix.[5]

entities.name: List of Formula One World Drivers' Champions

events.description: In Lebanon, pro-Iran kidnappers claim to have abducted American writer Edward Tracy (he is released in August 1991).
events.html: • 1986 – In Lebanon, pro-Iran kidnappers claim to have abducted American writer Edward Tracy (he is released in August 1991).

events.description: The Jaffna hospital massacre is carried out by Indian peacekeeping forces in Sri Lanka, killing 70 Tamil patients, doctors and nurses.
events.html: • 1987 – The Jaffna hospital massacre is carried out by Indian peacekeeping forces in Sri Lanka, killing 70 Tamil patients, doctors and nurses.

events.description: In Honduras, 131 people are killed when a Boeing 727 crashes on approach to Toncontín International Airport near the nation's capital Tegucigalpa.
events.html: • 1989 – In Honduras, 131 people are killed when a Boeing 727 crashes on approach to Toncontín International Airport near the nation's capital Tegucigalpa.[6]

events.description: North Korea and the United States sign an Agreed Framework that requires North Korea to stop its nuclear weapons program and agree to inspections.
events.html: • 1994 – North Korea and the United States sign an Agreed Framework that requires North Korea to stop its nuclear weapons program and agree to inspections.

events.description: In Seoul, South Korea, 32 people are killed when a span of the Seongsu Bridge collapses.
events.html: • 1994 – In Seoul, South Korea, 32 people are killed when a span of the Seongsu Bridge collapses.[7]

events.description: Images of the dwarf planet Eris are taken and subsequently used in documenting its discovery.
events.html: • 2005 – Images of the dwarf planet Eris are taken and subsequently used in documenting its discovery.

events.description: Iraq War: President Barack Obama announces that the withdrawal of United States troops from Iraq will be complete by the end of the year.
events.html: • 2011 – Iraq War: President Barack Obama announces that the withdrawal of United States troops from Iraq will be complete by the end of the year.[8]

entities.name: Withdrawal of United States troops from Iraq (2007–2011)

events.description: Thirty people are killed in a fiery bus crash in western Democratic Republic of the Congo.
events.html: • 2019 – Thirty people are killed in a fiery bus crash in western Democratic Republic of the Congo.[9]

events.description: In Canada, the 2019 Canadian federal election ends, resulting in incumbent Prime Minister Justin Trudeau remaining in office, albeit with the Liberal Party in a minority government.
events.html: • 2019 – In Canada, the 2019 Canadian federal election ends, resulting in incumbent Prime Minister Justin Trudeau remaining in office, albeit with the Liberal Party in a minority government.[10][11]

events.description: A shooting occurs on the set of the film Rust, in which actor Alec Baldwin discharged a prop weapon which had been loaded, killing the director of photography, Halyna Hutchins, and injuring director Joel Souza.
events.html: • 2021 – A shooting occurs on the set of the film Rust, in which actor Alec Baldwin discharged a prop weapon which had been loaded, killing the director of photography, Halyna Hutchins, and injuring director Joel Souza.[12]
